(11.4;0.5)</td>\n			<td>Typic Humaquepts(11.4;0.5)</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Ochrepts(654.5;29.3)</td>\n			<td>Dystrochrepts(654.5;29.3</td>\n			<td>Typic Dystrochrepts(434.0;19.4)</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td> </td>\n			<td> </td>\n			<td>Umbric Dystrochrepts(220.5;9.9)</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Ultisols(811.0;36.4)</td>\n			<td> </td>\n			<td> </td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Udults(437.0;19.6)</td>\n			<td>Hapludults(240.0;10.8)</td>\n			<td>Typic Hapludults(87.0;3.9)</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td> </td>\n			<td> </td>\n			<td>Typic Kanhapludults(153.0;6.9)</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td> </td>\n			<td>Paleudults</td>\n			<td>Typic Paleudults(197.1;8.8)</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Humults(374.0;16.8)</td>\n			<td>Haplohumults(273.3;12.3)</td>\n			<td>Typic Haplohumults(273.3;12.3)</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td> </td>\n			<td>Palehumults(100.7;4.5)</td>\n			<td>Typic palehumults(100.7;4.5)</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h4>Characterisation of Soils Under Different Agro -Ecological Subregions</h4>\n\n<p>The state comes under the hot and warm humid/per-humid agro-eco region. However, at microlevel, it can be divided into three distint-subregions(zone) with thermic and hyperthermic temperature regimes as follows:</p>\n\n<p>LGP : Length of Growth Period</p>\n\n<p>1.Warm-humid agro - eco zone with thermic ecosystem and LGP 300-330 days.</p>\n\n<p>2. Hot -humid agro - eco zone with hyperthermic ecosystem and LGP 270-300 days.</p>\n\n<p>3. Warm Per-humid agro- eco zone with thermic ecosystem and LGP 330-365 days.</p>\n\n<p>Table : Description of Agro ecological Sub-regions</p>\n\n<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Agro ecological subregions</td>\n			<td>Description</td>\n			<td>Area(percent of TGA)</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>17c</td>\n			<td>North Eastern Hills - Purvachal warm humid agro ecological sub region with deep fine red and lateritic soils of high to very high AWC(200-300 mm) and 330 days of LGP.</td>\n			<td>72.8</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>15d</td>\n			<td>North eastern Hills - Purvachal hot humid agro-ecological sub region with deep fine red and lateritic soils of high to very AWC(200-300 mm/m) and more than 330 days of LGP</td>\n			<td>12.8</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>17a</td>\n			<td>North Eastern Hills - Purvachal warm per humid agro-ecological sub-region with deep fine red and lateritic soils of high to very high AWC(200-300 mm/m) and more than 330 days of LGP</td>\n			<td>14.4</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h4>1.Soils of Warm Humid Agro-Eco Zone with Thermic Ecosystem(with LGP 300-330 Days)</h4>\n\n<p>The soils are derived from shale and sandstone and mostly occur on the hills of varying slopes. Soils occuring on the gently sloping foot hills are deep, well drained with greyish brown to yellowish brown in colour. Soils are classified as Type Haplohumults, Umbric Dystrochrepts and Ultic Hapludalfs.</p>\n\n<p>Soils on steep to very steep hill slopes are deep under thick vegetative cover and otherwise they are shallow with exposed stratified grey coloured shale layers. The soils are classified as Typic Kanhapludults, Umbric Dystrochrepts. Typic Udorthents, Typic Haplohumults and Typic Hapludults</p>\n\n<p>The soils are acidic with high organic matter content. Available phosphate is very low in the soils of upper reaches while it is very low in the soils of upper reaches while it is medium in the soils of narrow valleys which may be due to the formation of Ferric(Fe3+) phosphate or organometalic complexes not easily available to plant.</p>\n\n<p>Valley and fllod plain soils derived from alluvium are deep to very deep, poorly to moderately well draiend. The soils are slightly acidic to neutral with high humus content. The ground waterable is generally high and the soils are classified as Typic and Mollic Haplaquepts, Fuvaquentic Humaquepts, Typic Haplaquent and Typic Fluvaquents</p>\n\n<h4>Land Use</h4>\n\n<p>The upper reaches of the hills are under forest cover of decidous trees while mixed forest species comprising bamboos, wild bananas etc. occur in the lower steep hills. Jhum cultivation is practiced in places of convenient slope grades on medium hill ranges in normal cycles of 5-10 years. Maize, Sesamum, potato, Ginger, Tapioca and vegetables are grown under the shifting cultivation system. Horticultural crops like Orange, Pineaple, Lemon, etc. are also terraced on hill slopes and used for permanent cultivation.Scars of Jhum fields with secondary growth of vegetation are commonly occured. Valley lands are generally well bunded and used for intensive and permanent agriculture. The \' beel\' areas are occupied by luxurient growth of submerged weeds of mixed species.</p>\n\n<h4>Soil Constraints and potentials</h4>\n\n<p>The salient problems and potentials of the soils are:</p>\n\n<p>Constraints : Hill soils being acidic are not suitable for plant growth and traditional shifting cultivation along with indiscriminate cutting and burning of forests in every year in terms of timber, fire wood etc. have been affecting seriously the ecological balance of the area. Such practices leave the soil surface barren in addition to loss of fertile top soil surface through erosion. Water holding capacity is also reduced which again affect the availability of water in the lower reaches.</p>\n\n<p>The valley soils are mostly restricted to rice, but these are low in available phosphorous content and susceptible to flood hazards. Due to high clay content in places farming operation becomes very difficult.</p>\n\n<p>To sum up, the soil constraints are:</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>- Soil acidity</li>\n	<li>- Low action exchange capacity</li>\n	<li>- Soil erosion due to shifting cultivation and deforestation</li>\n	<li>- Low base status leading to toxicity of Fe and Al.</li>\n	<li>- Low availability and high phosphate fixation</li>\n	<li>- High ground water able and flowing in valley soils.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Potentials : The soils and agro climate of this hilly region are ideal for the development of horticulture. It is, however, necessary to establish nurseries for varieties specific for the region. It is also possible to exploit these soils for cultivation of tea.</p>\n\n<p>Bells and lakes can be utilised scientifically to expand and improve fish production in the are.</p>\n\n<h4>2. Soils of Hot Humid Agro-Eco zone with Hyper thermic Ecosystem</h4>\n\n<p>The agro eco-zone encompasses parts of Imphal(Jiribam area) Tamenglong and Churachandpur districts bordering Assam and Mizoram and occupies about 12.8 percent of TGA of the state. This zone experiences hot summers and cold winters with seasonal dry spells which even extend from November to April. The estimated length of growing period ranges from 270 to 300 days and moisture index ranges from 20-40 per cent. Mean annual precipitation of Jiribam station is 2088.7 mm and potential evapotranspiration of 1377.9 mm with an annual average temperature of 24.4o</p>\n\n<p>The soils of this region are heterogeneous in nature and developed in gently sloping narrow valleys and strongly sloping hills with moderate to severe erosion hazards. These soils are in general, well to excessively drained, fine to loamy skeletal and classified as Umbric/Type Dystrochrepts; Typic Udorthents and Typic Haplohumults. These soils are moderately to strongly acidic, humus rich and have low base saturation. Soils developed in narrow valleys are deep, poorly drained, fine in texture and with slight erosion hazard.</p>\n\n<h4>Land Use</h4>\n\n<p>The area is primarily under forest cover, sesamum potato, maize, ginger, tapioca and vegetables are grown under the shifting cultivation system. Horticultural crops like Orange, Pineaple, Lemon, Pears etc. are grown in these areas. Narrow valleys are cultivated permanently for Pddy and Maize in general</p>\n\n<h4>Soil Constraints and Potentials</h4>\n\n<p>The salient problems and potentials of these soils are :</p>\n\n<p>Constraints : Hill soils of this region are strongly acidic and have low base status and comparatively less moisture holding capacity. these are low in available phosphate contents and highly susceptible to erosion due to heavy and swift runoff over the steeps slopes. Due to shifting cultivation landslides and mass movement are additional man made problems of the region.</p>\n\n<p>to sum up, these soils suffers from :</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ Soil acidity</li>\n	<li>Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ Low exchange capacity</li>\n	<li>Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ Soil erosion</li>\n	<li>Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ Low base status</li>\n	<li>Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ Limiting soil depth in steep hill slope and</li>\n	<li>Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ Shifting cultivation and landslides</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Potentials : The soils of the region being highly acidic and base unsaturated, crops tolerant to acidity will grow effectively under such agroclimate. Horticultural crops like Pineapple, Pears, Peach, Plum, Lemon, Orange and Banana may grow successfully with proper management.</p>\n\n<h4>3. Soils of Warm Perhumid Thermic Agro-ecozone</h4>\n\n<p>This region comprising the south-western part of the state gradually merging to Mizoram has longest growing period. The land/surface configuration is mostly dissected hills with narrow valley. The region covers 14.4 per cent of the total geographical area of the state. The moisture is available through out the year barring some seasonal deficit during November, December and January. The estimated length of growing period varied from 330-365 days.</p>\n\n<p>The main soil types of this area include Typic/Umbric Dystrochrepts, Typic Haplohumults/Typic Udorthents and Typic Palehumults. The organic carbon content of the soils are high and have low base saturation and low CEC. Soils are highly acidic.</p>\n\n<h4>Land Use</h4>\n\n<p>The area is under mostly forest, Sesamum, Potato, Maize, Tapioca and vegetables are grown under jhum cultivation. Some areas are used for fruit tree crops. Narrow valleys are generally used for Paddy cultivation.</p>\n\n<h4>Soil Constraints and Potential</h4>\n\n<p>Constraints : The soils of this agro eco sub-region suffers from</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ Soil acidity</li>\n	<li>Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ Soil erosion</li>\n	<li>Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ Low base status</li>\n	<li>Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ Limiting soil depth in steep hill slopes</li>\n	<li>Ã¢â‚¬Â¢ Jhum cultivation and land slides</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Potentials : Soils of this region being highly acidic and low in base saturation and cation exchange capacity is preferred for crops tolerance to acidity. This region is also suitable for horticultural crops like Pineapple, Pears, Peach, Plum and Banana if planted under little soil and water conservation measures. this region is also favourable for agroforestry and other silvipastural systems.</p>'),(961,'<p><strong>Horticulture Schemes</strong></p>\n\n<h4> </h4>\n\n<ul>\n	<li><a href=\"http://pmksy.gov.in/\">1. PRADHAN MANTRI KRISHI SINCHAYEE YOJANA (PMKSY)</a></li>\n	<br>\n	<li><a href=\"http://rkvy.nic.in/\">2. RASHTRIYA KRISHI VIKAS YOJANA (RKVY)</a></li>\n	<br>\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.momamanipur.com/\">3. MISSION ORGANIC VALUE CHAIN DEVELOPMENT FOR NORTH EASTERN REGION (MOVCDNER)</a></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>State Plan Schemes</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li><a href=\"https://horticulture.mn.gov.in/schemes.html#\">1. ESTABLISHMENT OF ORCHARDS IN HILL AREAS OF MANIPUR</a></li>\n	<br>\n	<li><a href=\"https://horticulture.mn.gov.in/schemes.html#\">2. DEVELOPMENT OF FLORICULTURE</a></li>\n	<br>\n	<li><a href=\"https://horticulture.mn.gov.in/schemes.html#\">3. ASSISTANCE TO SMALL AND MARGINAL FARMERS FOR INCREASING AGRICULTURAL PRODUCTION – LAND RECLAMATION AND DEVELOPMENTSTATE</a></li>\n</ul>'),(989,'<p> </p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"color: #27ae60;\">Coming Soon</span></p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p> </p>'),(993,'<p><strong>B.Sc. Horticulture of 4 (four) years Degree Course</strong></p>\n\n<p>Every year the NEC/CAU offers seats for B.Sc. (Horticulture) Courses to the State of Manipur. Based on such offers, the Department nominates candidates based on 10+2 marks or Selection Test. Announcement for such nomination are usually made around May/June.</p>\n\n<p>1. B.Sc.(Hort) at Dr. Y.S Parmar University of Horticulture &amp; Forestry,Nauni, Solan, Himachal Pradesh</p>\n\n<p>No. of Seats : Announced every year.</p>\n\n<p>Eligibility: 10+2 or equivalent examination with English, Physics, Chemistry, Biology/ Mathematics/Agriculture of a recognised University/Board with a minimum of 50%.</p>\n\n<p>2. B.Sc(Horti) of 4-years Degree Course as State nominee at the College of Horticulture &amp; Forestry, Central Agricultural University, Pasighat, Arunachal Pradesh for North Eastern Regions.</p>\n\n<h4>Documents to be submitted:</h4>\n\n<p>The application form duly filled in along with the attested copies of Certificates and Educational Qualification accompanied with crossed IPO of Rs. 200 /- (Rupees two hundred, but the fee may be changed with time) only payable in favour of the Director, Horticulture &amp; Soil Conservation, Manipur should be submitted to this Directorate. The application form received after the due date will not be entertained. Incomplete application form and those not accompanied with essential certificates &amp; fee will be summarily rejected. No correspondence in this regard will be entertained. And declaration of list of eligible candidates will be noticed.</p>\n\n<h4>Eligibility :</h4>\n\n<p>Minimum qualification: 10+2 Secondary (10+2) in all subjects with 60 % marks in aggregate for General category &amp; 50% marks for SC/ST categories in Physics, Chemistry, Biology/Maths or Agriculture.</p>\n\n<p>Age: The candidate must attain 17 (seventeen) years of age.</p>'),(995,'<p><strong>Rogeny Orchards</strong></p>\n\n<p>For the development of horticulture in the right direction, adequate availability of quality planting material to the farmers is of importance, keeping in view that the 10 departmental Progeny Orchards located at different elevations suitable for specific horticultural crops are the only source to supply the planting material requirements, these progeny orchards were strengthened. These Progeny Orchards are located at the following districts /stations:</p>\n\n<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Name of farm/ Progeny Orchards</td>\n			<td>Purpose</td>\n			<td>Available Materials</td>\n			<td>Area in acres</td>\n			<td>Location</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Progeny Orchard cum Nursery, Mantripukhri</td>\n			<td>Conducting experiments&amp; demonstration,propagation of fruit Plants</td>\n			<td> </td>\n			<td>37</td>\n			<td>Mantripukhri 7 km. from Imphal near NH 39</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Cashewnut Devt. Farm Jiribam</td>\n			<td>Production of cashewnut</td>\n			<td> </td>\n			<td>30</td>\n			<td>Jiribam, 220 km. from Imphal at NH 53</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Progeny Orchard cum</td>\n			<td>Production of Horticulral fruit Plants</td>\n			<td> </td>\n			<td>40</td>\n			<td>Tamenglong</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Nursery, Noneh</td>\n			<td colspan=\"4\"> </td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Progeny Orchard cum Nursery, Tamenglong</td>\n			<td>Production of fruit &amp; vegetable seedlings, distribution to the farmers</td>\n			<td> </td>\n			<td>35</td>\n			<td>Tamenglong</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Progeny Orchard cum Nursery, Thawai Mahadev</td>\n			<td>Establishment of departmental orchard on experimental Station.</td>\n			<td> </td>\n			<td> </td>\n			<td>Thawai Mahadev, Ukhrul</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Progeny Orchard cum Nursery, Churachandpur Tuiboung</td>\n			<td>Conducting experiments, demonstrations on cultivation of horticultural crops.</td>\n			<td> </td>\n			<td>24</td>\n			<td>Churachandpur 62 km. from Imphal</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Progeny Orchard cum Nursery, Thanlon</td>\n			<td>Demonstration,Plantation of fruit plants on hill slopes</td>\n			<td> </td>\n			<td>22</td>\n			<td>Thanlon 60 km. from Churachandpur</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Progeny Orchard cum Nursery, Tinsong</td>\n			<td colspan=\"2\">Demonstration,Plantation of fruit plants on hill slopes.</td>\n			<td>20</td>\n			<td>Tinsong 16 km. from Thanlon, Churachandpur</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Progeny Orchard cum Nursery, Khongkhang</td>\n			<td>Demonstration,Plantation of fruit plants on hill slopes</td>\n			<td> </td>\n			<td>20</td>\n			<td>Chandel</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Progeny Orchard cum Nursery, Maram</td>\n			<td>Propagation of temperate fruit plants</td>\n			<td> </td>\n			<td>35</td>\n			<td>Maram 86 km. from Imphal, Senapati</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>'),(997,'<p><strong>Guidlines for plantation of: Fruits :Spices :Vegetables</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Potato</strong></p>\n\n<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Location ( Altitude wise)</td>\n			<td>700 -1650 m msl</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Soil</td>\n			<td>Any type of soil, Thrives well in sandy loam.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Varieties</td>\n			<td>Kufri Chandramukhi , Kufri Jyoti and Kufri Lalima</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Seed rate</td>\n			<td>25 to 30 q/ha or 6.25 to 7.5 q/sangam</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Selection of tuber</td>\n			<td>Tuber weighing 40-50 g with 2 to 3 eyes.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Seed treatments</td>\n			<td>If cut tubers are used dip them in Dithane M-45 (2 g/litre) for 10 minutes.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Time of sowing</td>\n			<td>a) Plain areas : October - November b) Hill areas : March - April</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Land preparation</td>\n			<td>4-5 ploughing followed by planking. Make ridge and furrow.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Manures</td>\n			<td>20 - 25 t/ha or 5 - 6.25 t/sangam</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Fertilizers@ N:P2O5 : K2O-100:80:100</td>\n			<td>\n			<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n				<tbody>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Fertilizer</td>\n						<td>Per ha</td>\n						<td>Per sangam</td>\n					</tr>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Urea</td>\n						<td>217 kg</td>\n						<td>54 kg</td>\n					</tr>\n					<tr>\n						<td>SSP</td>\n						<td>500 kg</td>\n						<td>125kg</td>\n					</tr>\n					<tr>\n						<td>MOP</td>\n						<td>167kg</td>\n						<td>42 kg</td>\n					</tr>\n				</tbody>\n			</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Method of application</td>\n			<td>Full quantity of SSP and MOP and half of the Urea should be applied as basal. Remaining quantity of Urea be applied as top dress at the time of earthing up.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Spacing</td>\n			<td>a) row to row - 50 cm b) plant to plant - 20 cm</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Inter- cultural operations</td>\n			<td>Do earthing up, within 30 days of sowing when plants are 15 cm tall.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Irrigation</td>\n			<td>5 to 6 light irrigation. Do not irrigate within 30 days of sowing</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Plant Protection measures</td>\n			<td> </td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Insect Pest/Diseases</td>\n			<td>\n			<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n				<tbody>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Symptoms</td>\n						<td>Control Measure</td>\n					</tr>\n				</tbody>\n			</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Late blight (Phytopthora infestation)</td>\n			<td>\n			<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n				<tbody>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Brownish to purplish black lesions on the leaflets and in stems, lesions enlarged rapidly and brown discoloration of the tubers followed by rots</td>\n						<td>Do not use diseased tuber for planting. Spray Copper oxychloride @ 2.0 to 2.5 g/litre or 9% Bordeaux mixture.</td>\n					</tr>\n				</tbody>\n			</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Cutworm</td>\n			<td>\n			<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n				<tbody>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Worms cut the young plant at ground level and bud on tender leaves and shoot during night.</td>\n						<td>Spray Chlorpyriphos 20 EC @ 2.5 ml/litre or Endosulfan 0.07% (2ml/litre).</td>\n					</tr>\n				</tbody>\n			</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td colspan=\"2\">Potential yield 200 - 250 q/ha or 50 - 62.5 q/sangam q/sangam</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h4>Brinjal</h4>\n\n<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Location ( Altitude wise)</td>\n			<td>Low to medium ( 850-1100 m msl).</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Varieties</td>\n			<td>Pusa purple Long,Pusa Kranti,Pant Samrat,KT-4,Sel-3,Sel-5.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Soil</td>\n			<td>Heavy soil, clay loam to clayey are suitable.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Seed rate</td>\n			<td>700-800 g/ha or 175 - 200 g/sangam</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Seed/Seedling treatments</td>\n			<td>Treat the seed with Captan or Thiram@2 g/kg.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Time of sowing</td>\n			<td>a) Pre-kharif : January - February(spring) b) Rabi : September - October (winter)</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Land preparation</td>\n			<td>Plough to fine tilth.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Manures (FYM or Compost)</td>\n			<td>10 t/ha or 2.5 t/sangam.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Method of application</td>\n			<td>Mix thoroughly in the soil 15 days before sowing.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Fertilizers@ N:P2O5 :K2O-120:60:60</td>\n			<td>\n			<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n				<tbody>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Fertilizer</td>\n						<td>Per ha</td>\n					</tr>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Urea</td>\n						<td>210 kg</td>\n					</tr>\n					<tr>\n						<td>DAP</td>\n						<td>130 kg</td>\n					</tr>\n					<tr>\n						<td>MOP</td>\n						<td>100kg</td>\n					</tr>\n					<tr>\n						<td colspan=\"2\">a) Row to row - 75 cm. b) Plant to plant - 60 cm</td>\n					</tr>\n				</tbody>\n			</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Inter- cultural operations</td>\n			<td>Irrigation immediately after transplanting till the root sets and from ten on as and when needed. Weeding and hoeing when needed.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td colspan=\"2\">Plant Protection Measures</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Insect Pest/Diseases</td>\n			<td>\n			<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n				<tbody>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Symptoms</td>\n						<td>Control Measure</td>\n					</tr>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Dropping and withering of infested terminal shoot.</td>\n						<td>Spray Endosulfan 35 EC @ 2 ml/litre or Monocrotophos 36 WSC @ 1 ml/litre or Quinalphos 25 EC @ 2 ml/litre or Fenvelerate 20 EC@ 0.5 ml/litre of water starting from one month after transplanting.</td>\n					</tr>\n				</tbody>\n			</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Potential yield</td>\n			<td>200 q/ha or 50 q/sangam</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h4>Cabbage</h4>\n\n<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Location ( Altitude wise)</td>\n			<td>900-1500 m above msl.(mean sea level)</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Varieties</td>\n			<td>Pride of India, Golden Acre, Drum head, Pride of Fuji (hybrid), Konark(hybrid)</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Soil</td>\n			<td>Heavy soil, clay loam to clayey are suitable.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Seed rate</td>\n			<td>400-500 g/ha or 100 - 125 g/sangam</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Seed/Seedling treatments</td>\n			<td>Agrosan GN or Ceresan @ 2 g should be treated with 1 kg of seed before sowing. After germination seedlings are sprayed with Dithane -45 @ 1 g/litre of water.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Time of sowing</td>\n			<td>a) Pre-kharif : March - November<br>\n			b) Rabi : September - June</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Land preparation</td>\n			<td>Thoroughly Ploughing too fine tilth.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Manures (FYM or Compost)</td>\n			<td>15-20 t/ha or 3.75-5 t/sangam</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Method of application</td>\n			<td>Mixed thoroughly in the soil 15 days before transplanting.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Fertilizers@ N:P2O5 :K2O-120:90:60</td>\n			<td>\n			<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n				<tbody>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Fertilizer</td>\n						<td>Per ha</td>\n					</tr>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Urea</td>\n						<td>183 kg</td>\n					</tr>\n					<tr>\n						<td>DAP</td>\n						<td>198 kg</td>\n					</tr>\n					<tr>\n						<td>MOP</td>\n						<td>100kg</td>\n					</tr>\n				</tbody>\n			</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Method of application</td>\n			<td>Basal application of 58 kg Urea along with full dose of DAP and MOP at the time of sowing 125 kg Urea should be top dressed after 30-35 days of transplanting.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Spacing</td>\n			<td>a) Row to row - 45-60 cm<br>\n			b) Plant to plant - 45 cm</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Inter- cultural operations</td>\n			<td>2-3 intercultural operation is needed, light hoeing is advised.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td colspan=\"2\">Plant Protection Measures</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Insect Pest/Diseases</td>\n			<td>\n			<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n				<tbody>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Symptoms</td>\n						<td>Control Measure</td>\n					</tr>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Infected leaves show yellowing at the margin of leaves, veins become dark,brown and vascular region of the stem become discoloured.</td>\n						<td>Treat the seed with hot water at 30oC for 30 minutes. Crops of the same family should not be grown for at least 3 years.</td>\n					</tr>\n				</tbody>\n			</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Diamond back moth</td>\n			<td>\n			<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n				<tbody>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Many holes are seen on the young leaves</td>\n						<td>Spray Nuvan 76 EC @ 1 ml /litre of water.</td>\n					</tr>\n				</tbody>\n			</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Potential yield</td>\n			<td>200-300 q/ha or 50-75 q/sangam</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h4>Cauliflower</h4>\n\n<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Location ( Altitude wise)</td>\n			<td>700 -1500 m msl</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Soil</td>\n			<td>Heavy soil, clay loam to clayey are suitable.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Varieties</td>\n			<td>\n			<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n				<tbody>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Early varieties</td>\n						<td>Late varieties</td>\n					</tr>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Early Patna</td>\n						<td>Pusa snowball</td>\n					</tr>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Pusa Deepali</td>\n						<td>Snow ball - 16</td>\n					</tr>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Improved Japanese</td>\n						<td> </td>\n					</tr>\n				</tbody>\n			</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Seed rate</td>\n			<td>a) Early varieties - 500-800 g/ha<br>\n			b) Late varieties - 400 - 500 g/ha</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Seed treatments</td>\n			<td>Agrosan G.N. or Cerasan @ 2 g should be treated with 1 kg of seed before sowing. After germination, seedlings are sprayed with Dithane M-45 @ 1 g/litre of water..</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Time of sowing</td>\n			<td>Early varieties - Mid July to 1st week of August. Improved Japanese - 1st week of September to last week of October.<br>\n			Late Varieties - November.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Land preparation</td>\n			<td>Thorough Ploughing to fine tilth.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Manures (FYM or Compost)</td>\n			<td>15-20 t/ha or 3.75 - 5 t/sangam</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Method of application</td>\n			<td>Mix the mixture thoroughly in the soil 15 days before transplanting.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Fertilizers@ N:P2O5 : K2O-120:60:60</td>\n			<td>\n			<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n				<tbody>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Fertilizer</td>\n						<td>Per ha</td>\n					</tr>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Urea</td>\n						<td>140 kg</td>\n					</tr>\n					<tr>\n						<td>DAP</td>\n						<td>198 kg</td>\n					</tr>\n					<tr>\n						<td>MOP</td>\n						<td>100kg</td>\n					</tr>\n				</tbody>\n			</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Method of application</td>\n			<td>Basa application of 30 kg Urea along with full dose of DAP and MOP at the time of sowing, 110 kg Urea should be top dressed in 30-35 days after transplanting.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Spacing</td>\n			<td>Early varieties - 45 cm x 45 cm<br>\n			Late varieties - 45 cm x 60 cm</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Inter- cultural operations</td>\n			<td>Weeding ,earthing up, covering of curd with leaves for early maturing varieties is advisable.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td colspan=\"2\">Plant Protection Measures</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Insect Pest/Diseases</td>\n			<td>\n			<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n				<tbody>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Symptoms</td>\n						<td>Control Measure</td>\n					</tr>\n				</tbody>\n			</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Black rot</td>\n			<td>\n			<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n				<tbody>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Infected leaves show yellowing at the margin, veins become dark brown and vascular region of the stem become discoloured</td>\n						<td>Treat the seed with hot water at 30oC for 30 minutes. Crops of the same family should not grown for at least 3 years.</td>\n					</tr>\n				</tbody>\n			</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Diamond back moth</td>\n			<td>\n			<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n				<tbody>\n					<tr>\n						<td>Many holes are seen on the leaves.</td>\n						<td>Spray Nuvan 76 EC @ 1ml/litre of water.</td>\n					</tr>\n				</tbody>\n			</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Potential yield</td>\n			<td>150 -200 q/ha or 37.5 - 50q/sangam</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>'),(999,'<p><strong>Local Market Places of the State</strong></p>\n\n<table cellspacing=\"1\">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td>District</td>\n			<td>Market/Location</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Imphal East</td>\n			<td>Lamlong, Kongba, Lamlai, Sagolmang and Jiribam</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Imphal West</td>\n			<td>Lamsang, Khumbong, Sekmai, Mayang Imphal, and Samurou,Khwairamband</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Bishnupur</td>\n			<td>Nambol, Bishnupur, Moirang, Kumbi</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Thoubal</td>\n			<td>Lilong, Thoubal, Yairipok, Kakching, Serou &amp; Wabgai.</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Chandel</td>\n			<td>Chkpikarong, Chandel, Pallel and Moreh</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Ukhrul</td>\n			<td>Ukhrul, Kamjong, Phungyar, Litan, Lambui and Marem</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td>Senapati</td>\n			<td>Mao, Tadubi, Maram, Senapati, Kangpokpi and Saikul</td>\n		